Eligibility criteria
We will include studies that reported the values and preferences of patients (including children, adolescents, and adults) with chronic cancer and non-cancer pain, with or without co-morbid health conditions, who use or do not use medical cannabis, as well as the values and preferences of their carers, on: 
1)	the relative values patients place on outcomes related to medical cannabis use (e.g. improvements in pain and function, side effects of medical cannabis such as sedation, dizziness);
2)	the tradeoff between patient important benefits (e.g. improvement in pain and function) and harms or burdens (e.g. sedation, dizziness) of medical cannabis;
3)	the attitudes and preferences for or against medical cannabis, or for different administration routes, ingestion methods, and ratios of THC to CBD of medical cannabis for managing chronic pain;
4)	factors that influence patients’ decision-making regarding whether or not to use medical cannabis, or their choice of different administration routes, ingestion methods, and ratios of THC to CBD of medical cannabis for managing chronic pain. 

We will consider quantitative (e.g. cross-sectional design), qualitative (e.g. participant interview, focus groups), and mixed-methods studies. 

Values and preferences are defined as the relative importance of outcomes or health states of interest related to medical cannabis use.[1] Chronic pain is defined as pain lasting three months or longer. A carer is defined as someone in a paid or unpaid role of supporting a patient with chronic pain, who is related or unrelated to the patient, and who is not a formal healthcare provider. 

If studies report a mix of pain types, they will be considered eligible if they report patients’ chronic pain outcomes separate from other pain outcomes, or if at least 80% of the patients satisfy our criteria for chronic pain. 

We will also review reference lists of the included articles and relevant systematic reviews to ensure all appropriate studies are examined for this review.

We will exclude:
1)	studies that did not elicit data from patients or carers directly (e.g. data elicited from health providers; information from databases of health records);
2)  studies that only reported health state values or quality of life of patients with chronic pain, not related to use of medicinal cannabis;
3)  studies that only reported the perceived benefits and harms of medical cannabis for chronic pain from patients experience (i.e., that did not report a value judgement on benefits and harms); 
4) studies that only reported correlation analyses of associations among demographic variables, other patient characteristics, and cannabis use for chronic pain;
5)  studies that only reported access to medical cannabis;
6)	case studies with less than 10 patients included;
7)  cost-effectiveness studies;
8)  studies published in languages other than English;
9)  abstracts and reviews.

Study selection
Before beginning each phase of the review process, we will conduct calibration exercises in which reviewers assess the same articles and discuss any disagreement, leading to a clarification and common understanding of criteria and process. 
After calibration, six paired reviewers  will independently screen titles and abstracts of all retrieved references. Subsequently, the reviewers will independently review the full text of articles deemed potentially eligible. Disagreements will be resolved by consensus and consultation with a third party adjudicator as needed.

